    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Crepidula aculeata</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_2345",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Distinctive species with an almost perfectly round, conical shell rising to a central sharp point. Last whorl greatly enlarged and flattened with an internal flat shelf that protects the visceral organs. Margin of shelf distinctly convex and lobed. Exterior of shell white, usually smooth but may be sculpted with small knobs.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_2346",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell up to about 15 mm in length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_2347",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Europe and Mediterranean down West Africa to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to far Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_2348",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Usually found singly or in small groups on other shells or the undersides of boulders or in other sheltered habitats.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_2349",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Filter-feeder, removing small particles from the surrounding sea water by passing this though the enlarged, sieve-like gills.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_2350",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Protandrous hermaphrodite, changing from male to female as growth proceeds. Eggs are laid in capsules that are sheltered under females and these hatch into crawling young without a free-swimming larval stage.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_2351",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The shell shape is distinctive. Progressively replaced by the larger (up to 45 mm) <i>C. helicoidea</i> from Algoa Bay eastwards. That species has a similar shell shape, but has radial ribs on outer surface that are tinged with orange-brown.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_2352",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 172).<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 57 ).<br><br>Wyatt, HV (1961). The reproduction, growth and distribution of <i>Calyptraea chinensis (L.). <i>The Journal of Animal Ecology</i>, 30, 283-302.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_2353",
